definition: "Interleukin-6 (IL-6) is a pleiotropic cytokine — a signaling protein secreted by multiple cell types including macrophages, adipocytes, endothelial cells, fibroblasts, and skeletal muscle — that coordinates the acute-phase inflammatory response and bridges innate and adaptive immunity. In acute inflammation (infection, tissue injury), IL-6 rises rapidly and drives the production of acute-phase proteins in the liver, including C-reactive protein (CRP), fibrinogen, and serum amyloid A. This is the appropriate and adaptive role of IL-6. In the context of chronic low-grade inflammation — the state called 'inflammaging' that characterizes metabolic syndrome, obesity, atherosclerosis, and biological aging itself — IL-6 is chronically elevated at low levels, driving ongoing tissue damage, insulin resistance, endothelial dysfunction, and accelerated cellular aging through multiple downstream pathways. The distinction between acute (appropriate, transient) and chronic (pathological, persistent) IL-6 elevation is central to interpreting this biomarker in a longevity context."
why_it_matters: "IL-6 sits upstream of many of the inflammatory mediators that longevity medicine tracks. hsCRP, which is widely used as a cardiovascular inflammatory marker, is produced by the liver primarily in response to IL-6 — making IL-6 more proximal to the actual inflammatory signal. Where hsCRP measures the downstream hepatic response, IL-6 measures a primary driver. This distinction matters because IL-6 is directly involved in mechanistic pathways that hsCRP is not: IL-6 directly impairs insulin signaling (contributing to insulin resistance), activates JAK-STAT signaling pathways that promote atherosclerosis and endothelial dysfunction, and stimulates the production of reactive oxygen species in multiple tissue types. Peter Attia and other longevity-focused clinicians have highlighted IL-6 as one of the most important inflammatory markers to track, specifically because of this mechanistic centrality. Population studies confirm that chronically elevated IL-6 independently predicts cardiovascular events, all-cause mortality, and cognitive decline — with effects that persist after adjustment for hsCRP, suggesting it adds independent predictive information."

